  <a href="#1" id="1">
   The Hubble Space Telescope's science instruments are on hold, unable to begin observations.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The Hubble had been on "safe mode" with all motion stopped
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   because of earlier problems in linking the high-speed dish antennas with a relay satellite.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Ground controllers then took the telescope out of safe mode
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   and began to run a 12-hour computer program
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   to monitor its health.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   It is now on a "normal control-all mode"
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   where its own computers and sensors guide it.
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   Hubble's systems were set at conservative limits for initial operations and
  </a>
  <a href="#10" id="10">
   that caused many malfunctions.
  </a>
  <a href="#11" id="11">
   With most resolved,
  </a>
  <a href="#12" id="12">
   the shuttle Discovery astronauts are preparing to return home.
  </a>
